The defendant Anthony F Jenkins was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of THC, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Negotiations set forth by the state and confirmed by defense.

Defendant advised of his constitutional rights and maximum penalties.  Defendant advised that he must provide a DNA sample and pay surcharge, if this conviction is reversed, set aside or vacated he may qualify to have the DNA sample data expunged if he meets conditions under the statute.  Defendant advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible. 

COUNT 1:  Defendant waived all rights, plead GUILTY and was examined as to the plea.The parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  The Court found the defendant guilty and ordered entry of Judgment of Conviction.  

Statements made as to sentencing by counsel and defendant.

The Court orders the defendant to serve 2 days of confinement with 2 days credit.

The Court orders the defendant to pay a fine of $200 plus costs, assessment, surcharges, and fees to be paid within 1 year (by 12-08-17); any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment subject to collections proceedings.  

Defendant advised of his right to seek postconviction relief.  Filed, Letter, Pretrial Incarceration Credit, and Notice of Right to Seek Post conviction Relief.
